Glomac, Kim Loong, Maybank, Sunway: Malaysia Equity Preview

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-04-01T00:15:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-01/glomac-kim-loong-maybank-sunway-malaysia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 0.9 percent to
1,545.13.        Glomac Bhd. (GLMC)  : The Malaysian property developer
said profit in the third quarter ended Jan. 31 surged 55 percent
from a year earlier to 16.5 million ringgit ($5.5 million) as
sales gained. Glomac was unchanged at 1.79 ringgit.        Kim Loong Resources Bhd. (KIML)  : The palm oil and cocoa
producer said profit in the fourth quarter ended Jan. 31 rose 36
percent from a year earlier to 15.8 million ringgit on higher
sales, according to a company statement. The stock advanced 2.8
percent to 2.23 ringgit.        Malayan Banking Bhd. (MAY)  : Maybank Islamic Bhd., a unit
of Malayan Banking, the countryâ€™s largest banking group,
completed the issuance of 1 billion ringgit of Islamic bonds.
The proceeds will be used for working capital, general banking
and expansion, Maybank Islamic said in a statement. Malayan
Banking, or Maybank, added 0.3 percent to 8.96 ringgit.       Quality Concrete Holdings Bhd. (QC MK): The building
materials supplier said its net loss widened to 3.64 million
ringgit in the fourth quarter ended Jan. 31 from 2.76 million
ringgit a year earlier, according to a company statement. The
stock gained 0.8 percent to 1.26 ringgit on March 30.        Sunway Real Estate Investment Trust (SREIT)  : The
property trust was successful in bidding for Putra Place, a
shopping mall, hotel and office development in  Kuala Lumpur ,
according to a stock exchange announcement. The purchase price
of 513.9 million ringgit will be funded internally and via bank
borrowings, the statement said. The stock was unchanged at 1.06
ringgit.       Talam Corp. (TA MK): The property developer said it had a
loss of 81.1 million ringgit in the fourth quarter ended Jan. 31
compared with a profit of 5.76 million ringgit a year earlier
after sales declined, according to a company statement. Talam
was unchanged at 9.5 sen.        TDM Bhd. (TDM)  : The palm oil producer said it proposed a
final dividend of 13.5 sen a share, according to a company
statement. TDM rose 0.4 percent to 2.87 ringgit.  To contact the reporters on this story:
